	    	8.20.4 Going Aviking- An MA Vanheim Guide
Author: Ferrosol


	    		8.20.4.1 Article

I decided to finally get around to writing the MA Vanheim guide I have been planning for a while now. Now a few disclaimers this guide is written for CBM 1.6 and while some of it may carry over into vanilla do not count on it. Also I should point out I am not a particularly skilled MP gamer so take any tactical advice with a large pinch of salt That said In the couple of MP games I have used this strategy I have had moderate success and a better player than me could likely do very well.

Strengths

Good Battle mages- MA Vanheim has some fantastic battle mages in the dwarven smiths and Vanadrotts. The Dwarves can put up the standard army buffs from earth (legions of steel strength of giants. Weapons of sharpness etc.) and cast fun stuff like Blade Wind Magma eruption and rain of stones. While the Vanadrotts can put up things like arrow fend, storm and fog warriors and come with the usual air battle magic lightning spam.

Fantastic Thugs- Another of MA Vanheim's strengths is its strong thugs. Recruitable everywhere Vanjarls make great raiding thugs and can put up spells like mistform and mirror image to protect them. With minimal investment you can turn them into solid raiders and starting a war with a cloud Trapeze paradrop of a dozen equipped Vanjarls can ruin someone's day.

Decent Troops- You have some excellent troops (Skinshifters and Einheres) some tactically interesting troops (Vans and Valkyries) and some reasonable cheap melee troops (Huskarls). All in all giving you a solid line up with some interesting tactical options

Weaknesses

Weak end game power- Probably Vanheim's single biggest weakness. You lack the end game paths that can help transform a strong position in the mid game to a winning position in the end game. All Vanheim gets with regard to the big end game paths is D1 and B2 so no astral, limited blood, (on expensive hunters) very low levels of death and no nature magic.

Expensive Infrastructure-- except for your dwarves all your mages are sacred meaning you will need temples and labs in every fort if you are going to produce them. Also your forts are really expensive (your only fort that costs less than 1k gold is a Swamp fort ) so you will need plenty of gold.

Lack of Magic diversity- Barring 10% randoms the only paths you get with more than one in them are Blood, Air and Earth. While Earth and Air are not bad on a battlefield this lack of diversity could cripple you in the long run.

Units

Huskarls (10g 12r) & (9g 12r)-- Solid but unspectacular units, A volley of Javelins can do a surprising amount of damage to anything in their way especially if buffed with strength of giants. I have a slight preference for the Spear armed guys due to them being a little bit cheaper and spears being a bit better weapons than axes. Also these guys have shields making them great arrow catchers to put in front of your Skinshifters in the early game.

Hirdmen (12g 20r) & ( 12g 22r)-- What do you get if you take a huskarl, remove the javelins reduce the map move to 1 and increase the price? If you answered a useless unit not worth recruiting give yourself a pat on the back. If you recruit these I will come round to your house and laugh at you.

Skinshifters (25g 7r)--- Ah Skinshifters lovely Skinshifters.... Sorry was daydreaming a bit there. These are your best troops no expectations. In their first form they come with a massive great sword which can do a hell of a lot of damage to anything in their way. Also in their second form they get three attacks a round making them ideal to kill any unit relying on defense for its survival. Skinshifters regenerate 2hp a round giving some protection against afflictions and a little extra staying power. Now they do have some weaknesses they are very vulnerable to archers but your Vanjarls/herses can counter that with spells like mist/storm/arrow fend and also vulnerable to enemy mages with AOEs which you can counter with your own mages and Valkyries set to attack rear or attack archers. Also a major problem with them is the expense while they are definitely worth the price at 25g a pop they can be hard to mass.

Einheres (20g 20r)- Your second powerhouse unit after the Skinshifters. These fill an interesting tactical niche, With their higher protection they can take less damage than Skinshifters from archers and the berserk increases their protection and damage at the expense of their defence. Also a berserk Einhere in a squad prevents that squad from routing. They do have their weaknesses though their resource cost makes them hard to mass and their anemic attack skill prior to being beserked means they have problems actually hitting things.

Van (90g 16r)- Sadly diminished from their days of glory when the game trembled before the might of dual blessed vans, The van cavalry still soldiers on a solid unit with a place in any Vanheim strategy. Now you may be tempted to relive the old days and take a monster dual bless for these but remember they are Capital only quite expensive and glamour is not the defence against arrows it once was. That said Van cavalry can have a place in your armies as flankers and as part of a stealthy raiding force lead by a Vanjarl or Vanadrott. That said though I rarely bother recruiting them instead tending to favour the Valkyries which offer much more tactical diversity.

Valkyries (60g 15r)- DUH DA LA DUH DUH DA LA DUH DUH DA LA DA. Sorry sorry could not resist that. A leftover from EA Helheim Valkyries are excellent units in support of normal armies they can be used to threaten and disrupt enemy archers can wreak havoc on mages in the back lines and can disrupt anything set to attack closest. Also if you can get someone who can fly and bless them (an Indy priest with winged boots? a Vanherse or Vanjarl with Stymphalian Wings?) they make great raiders to drop on enemy provinces.

Fayboars (75g 1r)- A unit that I have to admit slightly baffles me. Yeah I suppose they could be good tramplers if your opponent is using an army of hoburgs and you have an irresistible urge to trample them. Aside from that their main use is as ersatz bags of wine that cost gold instead of Nature gems so bring along one or two if you are leading an army into supply poor territory.

Commanders

Scout (20g 3r)- your bog standard national scout. Recruit Indies instead.

Herse (30g 21r)- A cheaper version of an Indy commander again not really worth recruiting.

Vanherse (160g 16r) (A1H1 Sacred Sailing Stealthy Glamour Leads 40 men) - A fairly useless commander only really worth recruiting if you cannot afford the much superior Vanjarls.

Vanjarls (280g 18r) (A2B1H2 Sacred Sailing Stealthy Glamour leads 80 men)- the workhorses of this nation. They are expensive but you will be wanting lots of them as you will be using them for everything. These are your bloodhunters (with a SDR), your thugs (with mistform a shield and a firebrand), your combat mages (with summon stormpower and escorted by a Vanadrott who can put up storm they can spam thunderstrike or orb lightning as appropriate), your principal troop leaders (Map move 3 80 normal leadership sailing makes moving troops easier) and your stealthy raiders (with an escort of van cavalry) Basically however many of these you have you need more as these will also be your main researchers.

Vanadrotts (380g 17r) (A3B1 110% AEDB H2 Sacred Sailing Stealthy glamour leads 80 men) (Cap Only)- the first of your two cap only mages. Each of the randoms offer different tactical possibilities.
Vanadrotts with an A random can forge Air boosters for your nation and can accompany your Vanjarls to put up storm for them without boosters later on you will want them to put up air domes and may use them to cast mass flight and also perhaps supply the other air battlefield buffs like fog warriors and Arrow Fend.
The E random Vanadrotts are less useful from a casting perspective but can cast watchers at Ench 3 which gives you a useful against opposing stealthy troops, Also the E random means they make the best thugs being able to add iron/stoneskin to their buffs.
The D random lets your Vanadrott remote site search for death sites and with a few death boosters could put up winds of death a useful if rather niche spell generally though these are either kept at home researching in the lab or going out with staffs of storms supporting the armies and is probably the least useful random.
Vanadrotts with a B random are you principal blood forgers and summoners they can forge some interesting items like boots of youth (not that they are needed much for Vanheim) and also black hearts which could be fun (a glamoured lightning flinging assassin? cool not really efficent but cool) also they can be used to summon storm demons and can with some empowerment be used to cast the other major blood spells.
Dwarven Smiths (180g 2r) (E3 110% FAED Mountain Survival 50%DV)- The second of your cap only mages and again the randoms offer different tactical possibilities All dwarves however can cast most of the army buffs with summon earth power (Conj3) and can spam blade wind (Evo 4) so they have a tactical role.
The F random dwarves are your forgers and battle mages you want these guys either in the lab forging fire brands charcoal shields and shields of gleaming gold for your thugs or on the battlefield first of all casting magma bolts (evo3) and later on aoeing it up with Magma Eruption (Evo6). A random dwarves can forge some interesting stuff like the Scutata Volturnus, Silver Hauberk and Shield of valour. As well they make good combat mages with Aimed Bladewinds (alt 1, Evo4) and Rain of Stones (Evo7) Also they can summon Gargoyles which make excellent counters to enemy astral users and if Gift Of Reasoned can make excellent thugs.
E4 Dwarves are your army buffers putting up strength of giants (Ench 3) Legions of steel (Cons 1) Weapons of sharpness (cons 7) Army of gold (alt9) also they can put out some large Bladewinds and with a pair of earth boots or summon earth power can cast such gems as Earthquake (Evo 5) and Petrify (alt6) and for a bit of additional punch an E4 dwarf with earth boots can cast Earth attack (conj 8) and can summon the various earth kings (also Conj 8).
D random dwarves have a number of interesting applications as well as being your death remote searchers they can also cast blight (alt4) to lower an enemies income and more importantly increase unrest. Also they are vital for improving your magic diversity as for the price of 35 earth gems they can cast hidden in sand (Ench 6) which gives you a good chance of getting at base an E1D2H2 Dust Priest with a 50% chance of another D random another 100% chance of getting +2 in FES and a final 50% chance of getting an F random greatly increasing your magic diversity.

Pretender Design:

Scales

Order/Turmoil: Vanheim has expensive castles, expensive mages, and expensive troops you pretty much always want Order 3.

Production/Sloth: A bit more tricky this one it depends on how much you intend to use Einheres. if you want to use them a lot you will want at least neutral scales. if however you intend to rely on Skinshifters you can afford some Sloth. I would recommend leaving it neutral though as the Einheres add additional options to your toolbox.

Heat/Cold: Vanheim prefers Cold 1 so you will want at least that to start with and I often push up to Cold 3 when I need more design points.

Growth/Death : I prefer growth 1 as although Vanheim lacks old age it helps mitigate the pop loss from blood hunting. Growth 3 is probably overkill but could be nice if you have points to waste.

Luck/Misfortune: Vanheim's heroes are nothing to go mad for. I would pretty much take Misfortune 1 or 2

Magic/Drain: Magic 1 always no exceptions. There are some nations who can get away with drain 2 Vanheim is not one of them.

Magic Paths:

Vanheim is only really strong in Air and Earth, everything else it has only a smattering of level 1s or 2s. Whichever pretender design you take you might want to think about filling some of those holes.

Air:- Vanheim does not need air on its pretender. An A4 Vanadrott with one booster can cast every Air spell in the game except the rather useless Fata Morgana and if you really want that just forge a second booster.

Astral:- One of Vanheim's biggest weaknesses is its lack of Astral access for forging and ritual casting. its access to astral mages is limited. Now you have a couple of ways to get Astral Access, Firstly you can rely on Indies which is chancy and relies on you being lucky to get Lizard Shamen or Crystal Amazon Indies. The second requires you to rely on summons from your pretender of which probably the easiest to cast are Hidden in Sand (Ench 6) which gives you a 33% chance of an E2S2D1 mage the catch being it costs 35 earth gems and can only be cast in wasteland provinces by a E3D1 Dwarf. One of the others summon is Summon Spectres (Conj 6) which for D3 has a 25% chance of giving you an S2D2 mage. The third and final way into Astral is taking Astral on your pretender. Generally you will want some combination of all three. I would reccomend taking at least S5 to forge Rings of Sorcery.

Blood:- MA Vanheim only gets up to Blood 2 so if you want to go into blood in a big way you will either need to empower or take blood on your pretender. I do not recommend the later because you need B4 to forge boosters and there are generally more important magic paths for your pretender to take. However at some point you may want to go down the blood school in which case empowering a blood 2 Vanadrott to blood 4 is probably not a bad idea.

Death:- MA Vanheim only gets access to D1 on its native mages which while not enough on its own to bootstrap up the D ladder, can at least site search for death gems, With which you can either empower a D1 dwarf (not recommended). Use Hidden in Sand (which gets you an E1D2 mage with a 50% chance for D3) or have your pretender do the heavy death lifting. Generally I use a combination of relying on your dwarves to cast Hidden In Sand and using your pretender to summon in death help (Conj 6 Gets you Koythaki which gives you for 30 W gems and a W4 D1 pretender a W3D3 mage which gives you decent access to two paths you lack).

Earth:- Your Dwarves cover most of your earth needs but you may want E1 or E2 so you can forge a crystal coin to buff your S magic.

Fire- Vanheim does not have much access to fire with only a 25% of Dwarves being able to get a F random. This is generally enough for basic forging but if you really need more F magic either take your chances with Hidden in Sands (which can get you F2 33% of time with an additional 50% chance of F3) or empower you might want at most F1D1 on your pretender to be able to forge a cheap skull of fire to enable your F1 dwarves to remote site search. Beyond that I find it hard to justify major fire access on your pretender.

Nature- Vanheim has no natural access to Nature so you want at least N2 on your pretender so you can forge a thistle mace and give it to an Indy Druid or Shaman and cast Haruspex hopefully getting some enchantresses or other good N mages while searching. Failing that you want N4 on your pretender which is enough to cast most of the main nature spells as needed. Also Naiads are an option if you take at least W2N1 on your pretender as they get you into Nature and Water at the same time. two paths you lack natural access too.

Water- while water in itself is not very useful it can be handy for getting into other paths that you want access too and a minor W bless of W4 can be handy for your raiding thugs. To get into water in a big way you either need rely on Summoning Naiads or summoning Koythaki in which case read the relevant Death and Nature sections.

Pretender Designs

Now to some actual pretender designs!

Build 1
Dormant Great Sage Dom6 O3 C3 G1 Mis 1 M1 F2 W4 E4 S5 D1 N4
This build is intended to be something of a jack of all trades build and is the one I have had the most success with. Your scales are decent enough that you can recruit enough troops to expand with. You have a half decent rainbow bless for your Vanjarl raiders, and the magic paths help cover the holes Vanheim experiences in its magic selection. This is probably the most flexible of the Vanheim builds allowing you to do almost anything and take advantage of the complete range of Vanheim's possibilities. When your pretender wakes up he should spend a few turns site searching and could perhaps consider putting up Strands of Arcane Power to make it easier.

Build 2
Imprisoned Master Druid Dom 6 O3 S1 C3 Mis 1 M1 F4 W2 E9 N6
this build is focused on taking a monster bless for you Vanjarl raiders it sacrifices late game power for an increase in your Mid game power. Taking this pretender commits you to relying on your Vanjarls to raid so simplifies the needed research goals greatly. with this build you will want to target Alt3 Enchant 4 and Construction 4 and rely on your Cloud trapeezing Mistformed Vanjarls to do the dirty work.

Research Strategy.

You have two major choices for your research.
One of which is to push down the Evocation School to Evo 5 for Storm. Then you can have a Vanadrott with A4 or an Air booster put up Storm which not only limits enemy archers and fliers but also allow all your Vanjarls to cast Summon Storm Power and then spam thunderstrikes or Orb lightning depending on what is best.

The other big early research paths are Alt 3 for mistform Cons 4 to forge some gear for your vanjarl thugs and Ench 4 for cloud trapeze. This strategy may take a little longer to mature but means you can drop Vanjarls which have been turned into a cheap thug (Usually a brand and a Shield is enough) on enemy PD and expect them to conquer the province. If done en-mass on the first turn of an attack it can win you the war in a single turn if it works.

Whichever way you choose initially you will eventually want to go down the other path to add a bit more flexibility to Vanheim.

After that Some other research goals to consider are:

Enchant 6 for Arrow Fend(fixes your Skinshifters biggest weaknesses) and Hidden in Sand(Magic Diversity).
Alt 6 for Fog Warriors and Marble Warriors (Army Buffs) and Petrify(your main SC counter).
Conj 5 and 6 for Summon Naiad and Waters of Hades respectively(Magic Diversity)
Conj 8 for the Earth and Air Royalty(your own SCs) and Earth Attack (one of the best assassin spells castable)
Blood 4 for Storm Demons ( a poweful lightning immune summon which synergises well with your armies)
Cons 8 (Artifacts although chances are others will beat you there.)

Strategies

Blood Sacrificing- MA Vanheim is one of only two MA nations that can Blood Sacrifice. So it might be worth taking a high dominion and perhaps trying to find a N mage to empower in blood to forge Jade Knives. MA Van is not the best at blood Saccing though with only H2 Priests but it could still prove a nasty surprise to someone who was not expecting a major dominion push. (Check out Kheldrons excellent guide on the topic for more information)

MORE TO COME LATER.


If you have any more suggested tactics please post or PM them to me and I will incorporate them into the guide



