		8.40.2


	8.41 Bogarus


		8.41.1 Bogarus Quick Guide
Article Author: DrPreatorious


			8.41.1.1 Original thread
There has been much *****ing in respect to the power of Bogarus. Let's start with a breakdown of the mages:

* Starets. The Star, indeed, the raisin deeter of the entire nation. Much hash has been made over their low cost - they cost the same as an Augur elder, the Augur elder is quite excellent, and the Starets is better. I don't view this is a balance problem - you recruit one every turn, which is the same number you'd recruit if the cost 75gp more, and, by and large, you are going to end up spending the extra money on your dismal military.
While their low cost is not that big a deal, their high total research output (regardless of cost), *is* a big deal, and gives Bogarus the sharpest early research graph in the game, sharper even than EA Arco.
In the long run, you actually don't have a research advantage on cost anyway. These guys produce 12RP/17gp/turn, compare to an Archtheurg at 9RP/13gp/turn. Over the long haul, it's sacred researchers that really pay off.
But in the short run you've got a huge leg up, and you'll want to take advantage of it.

* Master of Names. By and large, you will recruit one of these in every non-capital fort, every turn. When you have all the science, they turn into serviceable communion slaves.

* Kalendologist. The argument can be made for these guys, but personally I'd rather have more science and take the bad events.

* Alchemist. Recruit 1 or 2 of these - they'll search for sites (only earth you get) and may perform alchemy if needed. Even at +50% alchemy is not a great idea most of the time.

* Astrapelagist. Another site searcher. The event prevention is not worth the loss of research, most of the time, BUT these guys are your best bet for cheap combat mages out of the many, many fortresses you will be building. If you're at war (and you probably are), you'll want groups of 8 who will form a communion and spam thunderstrike.

* Occultist. The final leg of your native site searchers. You can use these guys to blood hunt, or you can use five fold angels, it's probably about a wash.

Note that this gives you F1A2E1S1D1B1. Pick up a couple of trivals to find nature, and the only site you're missing is water.
This is one reason I recommend *against* aiming for the water summons. No income.

* Five fold angels. Use them as blood hunters (the unrest is bad, but the low upkeep and second point of blood magic are good), or stealth preachers, as you like it. Skopets are amusing but I wouldn't bother.

military:
Dateline: Stalingrad, 1943
* Scum, from the huts of scum. To conquer indie provinces, you will be recruiting peshti of one kind or another (I recommend the axes, so that you can kill some heavy infantry) and voi archers.
These units suck, and you don't care if they die doing their internationalist duty. When they can't conquer anything else useful, you bring them home to be patrollers. At least they're cheap.
You can give 1/3 of them axes if you really want to extend the red army joke.

* You can use the Voi infantry as skirmishers if you have the patience (scatter them around in front of your real army to soak spells and arrows), but your peshti are expendable enough that I wouldn't bother.

* The cavalry are decent and only moderately overpriced, especially the medium cav with composite bow and sword. Their great virtue is that they aren't strat move 1, so once your past the very early wars, use these guys, or tribal archers and light infantry, or something other than your SM 1 national troops.
Even these guys aren't much compared to a real army, so mainly you'll be wanting chaff who can die in droves while your communion drops thunderstrikes.

* Khlyst are stealthy. This means they are actually better than flagellants. Not worth a bless, though, imo.

Pretender Design:
You *need* a supercombatant God. If you don't have one, your opponents are not going to sit there and allow you to build up an insurmountable research lead.

This is my build, you can vary it somewhat:
Prince of Death, Awake, Domstr 10, Earth 4, Death 5, 3 Order, 3 Sloth, 3 Cold, 3 Growth, 2 Misfortune.
A few notes:
* The extra point of cold is probably going to be cancelled during summer of year 1 (when it really matters), and helps to bring the edges of your dominion to the desired cold 2 more quickly.
* Your dismal military really cries out for 3 Sloth.
* Your capital is a great city which changes the relative value of certain scales.

== Early Turns ==
|1. Recruit a starets and a bunch of the archers. Send your PoD blind into the highest income-looking adjacent province (avoid forests, as dark vines can still kill him). Absolutely set him to attack - if he tries to use magic, that's bad.
Raise your TR to 150% and set your initial army to patrol. Your scout should be a prophet.
Alternately, raise your TR to 200% and have your scout sneak after your PoD, he'll build a fort on turn 2. Probably better to wait, though.

2-4. Build a starets every turn, and some scum if you like. Put all RP into construction. Keep your starting army in your capital until you have 1200 gp for a walled city, then lower your tax rate back down and build it in a nice-looking province. With a TR of 200% you can sometimes do this on the 2nd turn, but you miss out on a staret so it's not worth it.
Your POD should be wandering around killing stuff. Avoid enemy dominion, avoid amazons or undead provinces and dark vines. Avoid Hvy Cav unless dominion in the province is at least 3.
Once you have the money for a walled city, send your pile of archers and spearmen around conquering weak indies.

Turn 5 - Rerout your research to get const 2 and them thaumaturgy.

Turn 6 - You just got construction 2! Build the following:
Enchanted Sword, Pendant of Luck, your choice of:
Fire Plate, Fire Sword, Copper Plate (Fire Plate is usually what you want against an F9 bless enemy.) Have your God come home and get it.

If you have an opponent with weak dominion, your God can personally kick his *** now. More likely, your God is going to intercept your first neighbor to invade you (expect this next turn). Fighting inside your own (strong) dominion, he can stop pretty much anything at this point, and bite back against an enemy with anything other than a SC God of his own.
Early research priorities are Thaum 1 and Evocation 4, so that you can put together a communion of 8 Astrapalegists (4 masters, 4 slaves) to spam thunderstrike.
Then you probably want blood (for thug chassis as well as big piles of demon troops) and construction, or possibly enchantment (for flaming arrows) and alteration (for wind guide.)

Other Sundry:
1) Flaming Arrows + Wind Guide. You have enough fire and air to pull off both, so you probably should. Your national archers are an bang:buck ratio, but you'd probably rather have tribals for the improved strategic move.

2) PoD and risks. Your PoD is going to pick up a few afflictions. Try to avoid them but don't have kittens when it happens. Place him at the far rear of the battlefield (to avoid crossbow bolts) and set him to attack rear. This both minimizes his exposure to archery, and will hopefully inflict some morale damage on the front line infantry before they can turn around and get him.

Mostly they'll be pretty irrelevant (Chest Wound doesn't matter when you have no enc., Weakness and Never Healing Wound can almost be ignored, etc.) but there are a few that will end his career of conquest.
Use your research edge to beat everyone else to the chalice.

3) Stealth Communion Fun. See "stupid pet tricks". Make a master matrix, give it to a druid (or other stealthy nature mage.) Give him some nature gems. Send him along with four angels scripted to cast sabbath slave, and a bunch of Khlyst.

When they fight, he casts Mass Protection - tada, you get some kind of army!

Note that this is in-no-way worth a bless.
			8.41.1.2 Comments


		8.41.2 Age of Heroes/TheDemon's Tactical Guide
From Dom wiki: http://dom3.servegame.com/wiki/Age_of_Heroes/TheDemon%27s_Tactical_Guide

This is a wiki-only tactical guide to getting the most out of Bogarus, early- mid- and late-game. Don't expect a complete unit evaluation. Also, I agree with many of DrP's points in his quick guide, mainly his breakdown of the casters and the worthlessness of the infantry. If you want a caster breakdown try there.

I refer to the CBM mod in this guide because it is used in the majority of games on the official forums. However the majority of tactics can be used in the base game.

Vanilla Note: If you are NOT playing CBM 1.6+, then this section at the end is a must read.


Contents
[hide]

    * 1 Pretender Design
    * 2 First Turns
    * 3 Early Game: Lances and Arrows
          o 3.1 Expansion and Rushing
          o 3.2 Early Research
          o 3.3 Flying Dogs
    * 4 Mid Game: Gold and Blood
          o 4.1 Spending Gold, Earning Slaves
          o 4.2 Research and Combat Casting
          o 4.3 Killing Virgins
    * 5 Late Game: Armies of Darkness
    * 6 In Summary
    * 7 Vanilla Note

[edit] Pretender Design

You have great early research, decent lab mages, amazing communion ability and battlemages, good cavalry, terrible troops, cheap shortbows. You lack high 1 Earth or 1 Death and don't have any 1 Water or 1 Nature. That means an SC, but at the same time if you want to take advantage of Bogarus's unique features, you need strong scales.

I almost always take Order 3, Prod 0, Cold 3, Drain 3 and Dom 10. There's a very good reason I'm stacking income multipliers, so Order and Growth are very necessary. It might be viable to go Turmoil+Luck with a different set of tactics, but the tactics in this particular guide count on stacking gold income. The rest can be adjusted to taste but any Sloth is going to hurt your ability to mass cavalry. Drain won't hurt you early and there is a plan for mid/late. Luck doesn't synergize with Order and misfortune+drain opens you to the "magic is fading" event. As for the chassis:

    * Awake Prince of Death, 5 Death. You'll need to beg borrow or steal 30 1 Earth gems to get an alchemist to , but the PoD is a strong chassis that can be SCed in midgame and summon Tartarians in lategame without artifacts.
    * Awake Manticore, or 1 Air (script air shield). The CBM Manticore is a bit like the Kraken: tough high hitpoint and lowish pathcost. A flying pretender is also a large boon for this particular Bogarus early game. Once your expansion is over stick him in the lab and have him cast Gnome Lore forever. Biggest disadvantage? No hands.
    * Awake Wyrm, . Like a Manticore that doesn't fly but is a little tougher.
    * Awake Cyclops, and 1 less scale. Cyclops is a little weaker as an SC but he can hold a Hammer. Be very careful with him on turn 1. 

I don't go for water because with no water mages you'll have a hard time getting enough gems to take advantage of your summons. Nature can be done with tribal indeps.
[edit] First Turns

Turn 1: You need a turn 1 province, and it needs to have enough resources to make recruiting cavalry worthwhile. Avoid forests because of bloodhenge indeps; mountains then normal are the best bets. Don't forget to script the SC. Patrol 150% your starting army, scout prophet, recruit 3 cavalry, likely Styags.

Turn 2: Next you are looking for a fort location. Keep patrolling, get yourself an indep commander if you can and send your prophet after your pretender. Start recruiting Heavy Cavalry.

Turn 3/4: Sneak the prophet into the fort location the turn you take it and start fort #2. Don't be afraid to alch a few fire gems or skip recruitment if you're short. I keep my starting army patrol + overtaxing until the end of year 1, when I start to make archer hordes. Extra gold will give you the edge early on, which is when you need an edge.
[edit] Early Game: Lances and Arrows
[edit] Expansion and Rushing

CBM has two types of viable cavalry, the 30 gold 22 res Styag with their Standard, Light Lance and Composite Bow, and the 45 gold 30 res Malaia Druzhina, with their Lance, Sword and Shield. Early on I recommend the Heavy Cav, because they have a shield and lots of indeps are archers. Later you want a mix of both, because the Styag jives with Flaming Arrows and won't be broken by fear. You should be able to make a cavalry squad every 2 turns or so, so that covers year 1. If space is restricted, rush targets are anything vulnerable to lances. You also get Flaming Arrows really early so anything vulnerable to those with poor research should also be under consideration. Ping-pong your pretender between the enemy cap and friendly dominion and stealth preach to help out a domkill if necessary. Your 2nd fort needs a lab the turn before it goes up, and the Staret is mapmove 1, so you may have to move out of capitol much earlier. Once the fort is up, make an Alchemist to sitesearch 1 Earth and then crank out Astrapelagists.
[edit] Early Research

First research target should be Conj 3, then Enchant 5. As you reach Flaming Arrows you can shift production to hordes of Archers and a screen of Peshtsi City Guard. City Guard are also great to mass in peacetime thanks to cheap gold/high resource cost. For those of you unfamiliar a Staret can cast Flaming Arrows in CBM using Phoenix Power and 3 1 Fire gems. Don't neglict your cavalry in this stage. Lances will mess up giants, and light lances with composite bows are decent frontliners (use Fire, I wouldn't bother with Hold and Attack) against archer-vulnerable rushes like skinshifters.

If you are dying right now and you aren't going to be able to make Enchant 5 intact enough to deploy a big force of archers, here are some very early possibilities to help you along:

    * Thau 2 for Bonds of Fire.
    * Evo 2 for Lightning Bolt (useful against SCs and small numbers of elites), then Evo 3 for Fireball (spammable by Starets against armies).
    * Alt 2 for False Fetters, Blindness, Armor of Achilles, Earth Meld. You can only use the 1 Earth spells if your second fort is operational and you can recruit alchemists and Earthpower them with a gem, but Armor of Achilles will surprise giants. 

Other than Flaming Arrows, Conj 3 Enchant 5 gives a few nice options and one critical spell:

    * The CBM Firebird at Conj 3 is 1 per 11 Fire and has an AoE fire attack and awe. It's a decent early SC counter if the enemy SC is hard to hit, and can also be used against giants in the same manner.
    * The CBM Lady Midday at Conj 3 is 1 per 11 Air and is Flying Ethereal and Fear. Summon them in combo with Firebirds and they go 2/square. Fear + Awe + AoE is a potent combo, and in the mid-game you can use these + Winged Shoes as raiders. 

[edit] Flying Dogs

Your biggest baddest spell, however, is

    * Summon Simargl. In CBM just 21 Air gems gets you 5 of these badass 10-hitpoint flying dogs. Their selling point is Patrol Bonus 10. That means every cast of Summon Simargl gets you a 150% tax rate on any province. This is your competitive advantage, your One Reason to play Bogarus. You are better at the overtaxing game than any other nation in the game, LA Man included. It's also why Order and Growth are absolutely crucial; both add more multipliers to your income. Your cap, 10k+ pop provs, and eventually 8k+ pop provs all should get 150% overtaxed, in that order. Less than 8k is blood hunting territory. 

If you play Bogarus and you don't use Simargls you are missing out on your biggest strength. They are seriously worth it. Here's some math: your total income (the total ammount of gold you've earned in the entire game), assuming growth 0, is equal at 100% tax and at 150% tax after 53 turns. And that assumes that you haven't gained any territory with that extra front-loaded gold income.
[edit] Mid Game: Gold and Blood
[edit] Spending Gold, Earning Slaves

Simargls mean lots more gold. With your gold start building forts everywhere. Fortified Cities are great, since admin 50 increases gold income even more. Now you can start the Master of Names research machine. More gold means more forts means more researchers, this is why I think it's ok to take Drain to afford Growth. Keep sitesearching 1 Earth and take a few starets out to sitesearch the other paths.

Simargls also let you afford earlier blood hunting. They make up for the opportunity cost of 0% tax blood hunting. I recommend starting the moment you get up a temple outside your cap. Two Fivefold Angels per prov, with Saguine Rods once you have them and 0% tax should keep unrest at 0. If you reduce pop in a province to 7k by overtax-patrolling, the province can be converted to blood hunting and send the simargls elsewhere. If you've been reading blood hunting guides, what I do here has been called a gardening strategy and synergizes with growth scales. It takes a bit of effort to break into the best blood stuff, so build up a bank of slaves early and it'll make your life easier later.

Overtaxing has one disadvantage: you cannot turtle. Not that you should turtle anyway; without gemgens it's a loser's strategy. Go out and take territory, increase your gem income, spam more forts and Simargls. You should be able to outproduce every nation out there, even if they're bigger than you, so be aggressive with your armies. You can afford to take losses. They cannot.
[edit] Research and Combat Casting

After Flaming Arrows, the next research goal is Thau 1 Evo 4. DrP mentions in his quick guide communioned Thunder Strike using 4 master 4 slave Astrapelagist communions, and I totally agree. More slaves helps, as does an extra master to cast Power of the Spheres. This is a big reason why you wanted that early 2nd fort.

Research can branch a bit at this point. Get thau 2 for sitesearching. After that, any of: Thau 5 for Soul Slay, Const 4 for Saguine rods, Const 6 for Boots of Youth, Blood 4 for Demons, Blood 7 for Arch Devils, Ench 6 for Arrow Fend, Alt 4 for Wind Guide, Conj 5 for Bane Lords and Zmeys, or Evo 7 for Nether Darts.

Personally I like Construction, because not only do you get Saguine Rods and Boots of Youth, you also get Brands, Shields, Winged Shoes, Eye of the Void, Spell Focus, blood boosters, death boosters and a whole plethora of other useful items. Hopefully you can also make a hammer or trade for one, this is the one big disadvantage of the Bogarus midgame. Flying Shoes are especially nice because they give you a raiding force using Firebirds+Midday, something the 1-stratmove Bogarus needs. Put them on an Astrapelagist and hand out gems for Arrow Fend if possible, but sometimes it isn't economical or research-efficient. You can also use cavalry to raid, but not with the same flexibility.

Your Master of Names are your research machine, but they can be pressed into battle as Teleport + Magic Duelers, or as communion slaves and masters for astral spells like Soul Slay and Enslave Mind. Use fort time recruiting real battlemages too. You have two great battlemages. The Astrapelagist can handle all the air battle spells in a communion. He can spam lightning like the best of them. Other than lightning, there is a viable fear tactic using Frighten/Terror/Wall Shaker, False Horror, Real Horror, Demon Knights and CBM Firebirds+Lady Midday. Confusion and False Fetters are also great Air combat spells. The other battlemage is the Occultist. He's dirt cheap and he can cast Nether Darts. You can put him in a communion to boost his penetration, and he can add Reinvigoration to any of your existing communions. If you don't have Evo 7, he can cast Nether Bolt which will cover you where lightning does not. Send a non-communion Astrapelagist along with any of your big communions to spam Aim.
[edit] Killing Virgins

To get to high blood, for any nation, you need to take your best blood caster and start empowering. Once you hit B4, you can forge the blood boosters, which you can then distribute to your other good blood mages. Then you start empowering non-blood mages to get cross-paths access, and there you are you're into blood.

For Bogarus in particular, your paths are very well suited to summoning the good kind of devils and demons, which lends itself to large late-game armies of blood summons. Occultists can summon monthly Bone Fiends. These can be your chaff when you need to switch to a late-game army. More importantly, get Starets summoning monthly Storm Demons. Storm Demons are amazing artillery that absolutely rip apart even summoned armies, since it's impossible to get troops to 100% lightning resistance unless they come with some innate. They can be str boosted for more damage, and work under Darkness and Storm. Forge Soul Contracts for Devils. Occultists can also be handed boosters and cast Blood Rite for vampires, but their usefulness depends on your dominion strength. And if you're using fear spam tactic with your battlemages, Demon Knights can be summoned by blood empowered Alchemists.

When you hit Blood 7, you get access to the Arch Devils. The earlier you get here, the better, since most of the competition also has 1 Fire+1 Blood. Summon as many of them as you can; they are effective thugs and can be effective SCs with the right equipment. At the very least, you can have them fly in with a little equipment, and spam Flame Eruption. Phoenix Pyre is great too, but Alt can be a neglected path for Bogarus until late game. You also get Vampire Lords at Blood 7, who give you good death access. I use them in battle as death mages, especially to cast Darkness. Although I've never seen a need to use vamps as a main force for Bogarus, you have the gold to spam temples to leverage immortality. Baalz's guide to vamps is a handy resource if you go down this route. The Heliophagi at Blood 8 are also often overlooked, and will also get you into high death.

While I'm on the subject, blood gives you Reinvigoration, Horrors, Hellbind Heart, Leech, Rush of Strength, Infernal Prison, and (in Const) Soul Contracts, Axe of Hate, and Lifelong Protection. Don't ignore blood. Also, eventually you want to move all your Starets out of the cap, then cast Dome of Corruption on it. This will keep your Staret recruiment safe.
[edit] Late Game: Armies of Darkness

Arch Devils and Heliophagi, Tartarians + Gift of Health, communions of penetration-boosted Soul Slay and Enslave Mind, huge communions of Nether Darts spam, armies of Darkness with Undead, Storm Demons and Devils. Master Enslave can be done by communion. Your best 1 Astral mage will need empowerment for Wish or Nexus, but you have all the boosters.

It should be possible to forge the Starshine Skullcap -> Crystal Coin -> Ring of Sorcery -> Ring of Wizardry -> Robe of the Magi with your Starets and an Alchemist, which will let you access the Air Boosters, which will let you access a whole bunch of goodies including Fog Warriors. Alt becomes more important in the lategame, and eventually you'll want Fog Warriors, Darkness, Army of Lead and Will of the Fates for your demon armies. Wish is a nice prize too.

There are a lot of options in late game; I can't possibly cover them all. If you've made it to this point, do whatever it takes to win. You have high access to the three excellent lategame paths: Blood, Astral, and Death (through Vamp Lords or Heliophagi).
[edit] In Summary

    * Cavalry provides the leverage you need to survive year 1.
    * An awake SC attack on turn 1 gives you earlier resources so you can recruit cavalry, and is an additional deterrent year 1.
    * Your starting army and most of your recruitables are extremely bad, and is best left on patrol duty until very disposable units are needed.
    * Your Starets get you Flaming Arrows very early, turn 13 in CBM, turn 10 in vanilla.
    * Forts early and often let you spam communion-capable battlemages. The Astrapelagist for lightning, and the Occultist later, for Nether Darts/Bolt.
    * Forts early and often let you spam research-bonus astral mages. The Master of Names useful in the endgame in large communions, for enslave mind and soul slay.
    * Simargls let you stack overtaxing onto great income scales, letting you spam forts early and often, and making your territory much more gold-efficient than your opponents.
    * Blood summons give you both late-game troops and mid/late-game SCs.
    * Death on your pretender and bootstrapping nature using tribals might let you access tartarians.
    * Earth income is a problem and you need to sitesearch early and trade to get good earth access.
    * High astral access is possible because you have S3 mages and can forge all the boosters. 

[edit] Vanilla Note

    * Gem Generators: every vanilla game should at least consider them. Your 1 Water summons can access Clams, so having 1 Water on your pretender is nice. Rusalkas will get you into the water, Vodyanoys will forge Clams and 1 Water items. Alternately, just summon a Beregina. Blood Stones are easy with a 1 Blood empowered Alchemist. No need to mess with Fever Fetishes.
    * Simargls are 1 per 11 Air. They're still the best thing the nation has. You'll need to dedicate several Astrapelagists to cranking them out, yet another reason to spam forts.
    * Firebirds have no AoE, which makes them worthless.
    * The PoD is only 75 points, making him my pretender of choice for most purposes.
    * Cavalry cost more resources. I advocate Prod 1 in Vanilla. Don't take Sloth whatever you do.
    * Styags are 50 gold, and therefore inefficient. Buy more archers or more Malaia Druzhina. The heavy cavalry is still great!
    * Other CBM->Vanilla features don't affect the overall strategy much. 

Vanilla pretender suggestions:

    * Awake Wyrm, , Dom 10, Order 3, Prod 1, Cold 3, Drain 3.
    * Awake Cyclops, , Dom 9, Order 3, Prod 0, Cold 3, Growth 2, Drain 3.
    * Awake Prince of Death, , Dom 10, Order 3, Prod 0, Cold 3, Growth 3, Drain 3.
    * Awake Prince of Death, 5 Death, Dom 10, Order 3, Prod 1, Cold 3, Growth 1, Drain 3. 

For a vanilla pretender, you'll have to sacrifice one of Scales, Water, or Earth access. Up to you. 


		8.41.3 A glance at Bogarus
Article Author: Executor

I'm here to present a different view on Bogarus. I think Bogarus is a grossly undervalued nation and few realize it's potential.
I've heard a lot of regards how it's hard to ulilaze Bogarus properly, that they have sucky troops and need an awake pretender, that they're a rush target and so on.

I'm going to present a strategy that unlike most won't compensate it's weaknesses but rather apply to it's strengths which are more than enough to cover it. And I won't be goinf on about troops/mages/ summons and stuff cause you can look for all that yourself. This is just a general idea as how to best utilize Bogarus.

Pretender Build > Imprisoned Oracle S6, Dominion 8,
O3 P3 C3 G3 L3 M3.
Basically all positive scales with the cold 3 for protection.

Ok, so, Bogarus starts with a rather crappy army. The initial expansion for the first few turns might be a little harder, but as soon as you take the first 2-3 provinces around your capital it gets much better.

Bogarus has great administration, 60, which combined with production 3 will enable you to recruit a good amount of Bogarus elite cavalry every turn, which will in most cases take out indie provinces with little to no casualties. Note that administration gives you more gold too, so the better the scales the more gold you'll get from your forts.
In the end, most probably, you won't be able to over-expand like a bless nation, but you'll have a fair amount of lands and won't stay behind on provinces compared to rest.

The point is that with these scales you can even afford to stay behind with provinces unlike other nations. Yes, you'll maybe have fewer provinces, but you won't be lacking in either gold, gems or research.

The awesome scales will provide you an excellent income for forts and troops which you'll be able to boosts even further in no time.
Your capital mages Starets, are probably the best researchers in the game, add to that a +2 research bonus, and you'll have a 14 research mage that has great paths, and cross paths, and isn't even expensive for his worth.

So, what do you do? You'll have enough money to buy top notch troops and Starets every turn. While you start to expand, use the Staretes to research Simargls (winged dog summons). They are great patrollers, +10, flying, which means even better patrolers, and are cheap, easily massable and easily accessible. You can summons them with Startes, they only cost 2air gems and you get 5.

Around turn 10 you'll already be able to double taxes on your
capital for a 1000+ gold income from just the capital using the summons for patrolling. It's kinda like the Pan strategy with using the harpies to boosts the income, only difference is that in this case you'll get double the money due to great scales.

You'll end up sacrificing a few thousand people for an insane amount of gold which you'll use to build a fort every other turns. After a dozen turns you can stop taxing your capital, or not, however, obviously you continue patrolling, and start patrolling in all your forts to further lower the chances of getting attacked. The less the enemy knows about your military capabilities the less likely they'll attack. Add to that the cold 3 scale that will ever further help you evade any potential invasion with any nation that doesn't have a cold preference itself.
And besides, LA nations generally have a high resource demanding troops, so once you bring up the first few forts you'll be able to top most nations in military production, and you'll field ,although more expensive troops (which won't matter mcuh cause you'll have plenty of gold for them), but better troops than the most, and not to mention cavalry, and archer cavalry on top of that.
Leave the growth 3 scale to slowly repopulate your capital, not much harm done.

Gem income. Staretes are great site searchers, once you get your economy running you can start sending them out to quickly site search your provinces while you shift the rest of your mages to research some defensive spells just in case.

Bare in mind that you'll have a great research lead compared to any other nation, and that you'll be able to change your research to what you need to defend yourself rather quickly.
Once again, Startes are great as battle mages. Get thunderstrike
(you can use gems on the A2 Startes to cast them), you can skellyspam in combination with sulphur haze (a combination that can defend you from pretty much anything not regenerative or undead early on), etc... Most LA nations lack proper magic power like EA and MA nations, and Bogarus has most paths covered, and great cross paths that puts them ahead of any other LA nation magic vise.

So now you have a great gold income, forts poping up all over the place to boosts your research and help you mass your elite troops, great gem income from manually site searching with Staretes, and than remote site searching for what's left and a great research lead compared to most nations that will get you to construction 8 first probably. And having luck 3 will give you even more gems and gold on top of all that. Pretty nice huh?

At this point you'll potentially raise to be the strongest nation, which will lead, or be near the top with income, forts, research and gems. The 4 graphs that count...
