Actually, jade knives are far more unbalancing on small maps, because there are many fewer territories that aren't yours, and thus its easier to spam your dominion to the four corners of the map.

Further, getting your 'dominion' up to 10 by building temples doesn't actually increase your dominion in any real sense, just the number of candles you can have per province (with associated per candle effects, like more sacred recruitables). Your temple checks, however, are unaffected by this change, so your ability to fight dominion spread is only increased insofar as you have more temples. You're still producing dom 5 checks against dom X spread.

So consider a small map with 4 players, say 60 provinces. Lets assume everyone has 15 provinces, that the blood sacker has dom 10, and that the other players have dom 5. We'll further assume each player has 5 temples, and has miraculously maxed their dominion in-territory.

Each defending player produces 5 temple checks per turn generating on average 2.5 candles.

The blood sacker we'll assume has 5 H2 priests with Jade Knives. They're generating 9x5 = 45 temple checks per turn, and each of those checks is a guaranteed candle. Note this requires the tiny investment of 20 slaves per turn.

Assuming pretenders and prophets are alive, that's another potential 2.5 candles per defender, and another 4 candles for the dom sacker. And the prophet could replace one of those H2 priests for another 2 candles per turn at the cost of 1 slave.

Starting candles:
Bloodsacker: 150
Defenders (each): 90 (6/province)
Total defending candles: 270

Candles/turn
Defenders: 5
Blood Sacker: 51
Net difference: 36
Minimum turns till map-wide dominion kill: 9
Maximum turns till map-wide dominion kill: ~20

Note that the blood sacker is making a minimum investment here. Its 21 slaves and 5 priests. He's still perfectly capable of fighting wars. Chances are, if he were pursuing this strategy, he'd have built more temples, so he'd actually have a larger dominion spread advantage. Chances are his opponents wouldn't have built as many temples either, and they'd have fewer starting candles on the map relative to maxed out than the dom sacker would because they have lower candle generation and the dom10 would likely be pushing into their territory.

If the blood sacker is smart, he also built up enough slaves to win the game before starting the dom push. It could be as few as 180 with these generous assumptions for the defender. Chances are 250 slaves in a real 4 person game would be enough to win a dom sack victory without any difficulty - which is *maybe* 4-5 turns of hunting once a blood economy gets off the ground.

And none of this stops the blood sacker from outplaying an opponent militarily while he's gearing up for this, since the investment is so minimal.

Provinces/player tends to stay relatively constant with game size, but to win by blood sacrifice you need to get your dominion to cover the map, meaning you have relatively more work to do the larger the map gets.

----------------
TLDR; jade knives made blood sacking way too strong, *especially* for small maps. Blood sacking is still really strong even without jade knives.

