Calahan :
Diceman and Squirrel - Ok, I'm not 100% sure what either of you are talking about, and it seems both of you are trying to put words into my mouth. eg. I can't see where I made any claim that the number of temples you have increases the strength of your temple checks, yet you both seem to suggest that I do. My post might be confusing, as I was writing it from my understanding, which seems contrary to both of yours (and with a slight hangover). And some confusion might be over the different terms, as current dominion strength and current temple check strength are two different things in my mind (the latter being fixed at design stage)


Anyway, what I want to (try to) do now is explain how Dominion spread works as far as I understand it. I am not an expert on the dom spread mechanics by any means, nor have I tested it to the level of magnifying glass, clipboard, and Deep Blue on standby to analyse results. I have done some testing in the past though, and also did some brief testing today.

The manual isn't correct on dom spread, and having checked, it is a bit more wrong than I remember it being. But it does appear to be correct on a few of the formulas. (but it does of course get some things quite wrong)

So here is my understanding of the Dominion spread mechanics.

-------------------------------------------

(disclaimer - all of the following is just my understanding. I make no claims to it being 100% correct, and I'd be more than happy to see any evidence that indicates the contrary on any of this)


To begin with, one important thing to understand is that actually gaining a candle on the map is a two-step process. A successful temple check, and then subsequently gaining a candle is not an automatic guaranteed process, as there are checks involved, and some failed checks can see the candle created from the temple check lost. ie. I am saying that the candle from a successful temple check does not have to go somewhere. (which I am presuming both of you are claiming)

The first step is the temple check. This decides whether or not a 'wandering' candle is created or not. This equation is

10% x (starting) Dominion Strength.

This is (almost) from the manual, and as far as I know it is correct. Albeit with the added (brackets) correction that only your starting dominion strength counts (and not as the manual claims, your current maximum dominion strength). Although if someone wants to point me to testing and evidence that this formula is incorrect, then I'd welcome the chance to learn the actual formula.

If the above equation is correct, then a dom 10 Pretender will always create a 'wandering' candle from every temple check.



The second step is for the 'wandering' candle to try and find a home. Note it does not have a guaranteed home unless it meets a province with neutral dominion. (when the chance of the 'wandering' candle settling there is 100%). The manual claims that a 'wandering' candle has to find a home, but I do not believe this to be the case. (which I will address in 3 below).

So given a successful temple check, the 'wandering' candle created first checks the province it is created in. If this fails, then it moves to a random connecting province to again try to find a home. This 'wandering' candle then has three types of provinces it can encounter. If it encounters......

a..... a province with neutral dominion - It has 100% chance of settling, and you gain a candle. This is from the manual , and I believe it to be correct. (page 93. "If the dominion in the province is neutral, dominion increases to +1 automatically")


b..... a province containing positive dominion - A check is made to decide whether your 'wandering' candle settles or not. The following formula is from the manual, which I believe to be correct.

Chance of number of your candles increasing in a province already containing your candles = 30% - (number of candles currently in the province x 3%).

If a successful check is made, then you gain a candle in that province. If the check fails (in a friendly province), then your 'wandering' candle continues its journey.

This means a province with 1 candle has a 27% chance of increasing if checked by your ''wandering' candle, and at 9 candles you only have a 3% chance of your candles increasing to 10. This is why your dominion always spreads out before it fills up. Since the more candles you have in a province, the more failed checks you will have.

This is what I said, or at least tried to say, in the first paragraph of my post. ie. your dominion strength (not temple check strength) affects your dominion spread. As the stronger your dominion is (ie. the more candles you have) the less chance you have of gaining more candles.


c..... a province containing enemy dominion - A check is made to decide whether your 'wandering' candle settles, and thereby reduces the number of enemy candles by 1. The formula for this in the manual is also correct to the best of my knowledge.

Chance of a 'wandering' candle reducing the number of enemy candles by 1 = 50% + (your starting dominion strength x 5%) - (current number of enemy candles in the province x 5%)

If a successful check is made, then the number of enemy candles is reduced by 1.

Now the crucial difference

If an unsuccessful check is made, the 'wandering' candle is extinguished. (this is the complete opposite of what the manual claims)

So a 'wandering' candle from a 10 dominion Pretender journeying to a province with 10 enemy candles has a 50% chance of reducing that number to 9, and if it journeys to a province with 2 enemy candles, then it has a 90% chance of reducing the number of enemy candles to 1.

This is why a high 9/10 dominion strength Pretender always spreads dominion so well, since it has a very high chance of reducing any low levels of enemy dominion it meets. Whereas a dominion strength 5/6 Pretender, often struggles to reduce enemy dominion.


So if you have 10 positive candles in your province, then the best chance the enemy has to reduce it with temple checks is 50%, which has to be a 'wandering' candle from a Dominion strength 10 Pretender. (This is what I was referring to in the last paragraph of my post.)

---------------------------------------------------

Now I guess the most controversial claim I am making here is that a successful temple check isn't guaranteed to produce a candle, which (I think) is what the manual claims. And that your 'wandering' candles are lost when they encounter a province with enemy dominion, combined with an unsuccessful check. The current theory is that a successful temple check is guaranteed to produce a candle somewhere. But I believe this to be mistaken, and here is a simple test I did some time ago (and again today) in an attempt to prove it.


I started a game on a linear nine province map, so all the provinces are in a line 1-2-3-4-5-6-7-8-9.

I started a two nation test game with two Dom 10 Pretenders. One starting at province #1, the other at #9. I captured all the provinces (to check for random event that might effect number of candles), killed both gods (to stop any auto candle gain messing with results), and allowed the province to fill-up with dominion. After many turns, as expected, provinces 1-4 and 6-9 filled up with 10 candles of the respective nation. While the middle province #5 obviously saw something different......

Now, if a successful temple check produced a 'guaranteed candle somewhere', as seems to be the claim of the manual (and some players), then the dominion in province #5 should never change. Both nations had a capital and a temple, so both were producing the same 3 temple checks. Neither nation had a prophet or god, and neither nation saw any events that changed dominion levels. Both nations were also producing Dominion strength 10 temple checks. ie. all temple checks were guaranteed to produce a 'wandering' candle.

So, if the claim is that each nations 3 'wandering' candles are guaranteed to produce a candle somewhere, then the total number of candles (in this scenario) has to stay the same. As if each candle is guaranteed to gain a candle somewhere, then each candle is being automatically cancelled out by the equivalent 'guaranteed to settle somewhere' candle of the other nation.

But this is not what I observed at all. As the number of candles in province #5 fluctuated quite a bit, and the number of candles never got higher than 7 to any nation. The only thing that seems to explain this is if 'wandering' candles can be extinguished, and this means that a successful temple check is not guaranteed to produce a candle somewhere.

Now I have a feeling (as it was generally before my time) that this 'guaranteed to produce a candle somewhere' mechanic is what was responsible for the dominion 'jumping' bug that was sometimes seen in games. ie. your dominion would suddenly appear on the other side of the map. ie. It HAD to go somewhere, so it found a neutral dom province on the opposite end of the map. But I believe this bug was fixed in one of the patches (I think I started playing Dominions somewhere around the time this bug was fixed, so my only knowledge of the bug is what I have read in older shrapnel forum posts)


I also did a further test to confirm this.

Using the same map, I started the same two nations under the same conditions as before (ie. no prophet, checked for events, and killing both gods straight away).

This time one nation started in province #1, and the other nation in province #2. The idea of this test was that if the 'wandering' candle from the nation in province #1 failed the check (due to the enemy dominion) at province #2, then if it was not extinguished (ie. based on the theory that it had to go somewhere) then it would surely journey onto province 3-9 until it did settle somewhere.

But this didn't happen either. The nation in province #1 never gained any dominion in provinces 3-9 while nation #2 had postive dominion at it's capital. Some dom spread by nation #1 to province #3 was seen when nation #2 briefly lost dominion at its capital. (and this followed rule #1 from above regarding dom spread in provinces which already have postiive dominion). Surprisingly, provinces 8-9 were actually dominion neutral for most of the test. (about 50 turns)

Also, nation #1 really struggled to maintain dominion, while the nation in province #2 had an easy time. This is because some of the 'wandering' candles of nation #1 were being extinguished on the capital of nation #2. While the 'wandering' candles for nation #2 that were forced to journey (by failing a check at its own capital), had a 50% chance of going towards province 3-9, and an almost certain chance of gaining a candle.


So to summarise my understanding of the dom spread mechanics.

Just because a candle is created by a successful temple check, this doesn't mean it HAS to go somewhere. It has a % chance to end up somewhere, and if you have a high dominion Pretender, then it has a very high % chance of going somewhere. But there is no guarantee that it will (unless it meets a dominion neutral province, when it has a 100% chance)


I have not conducted rigorous tests on dominion spread, and it is also a right bugger to try and understand where in the debug-log dominion spread data is (and I'm still very much in the learning stage with regards debug log reading). But what tests I have conducted, and from my experience of playing, my current belief is that what I say in my conclusion is correct as I understand it.

But as I said, if someone can point me to actual testing and evidence to the contrary, then please do, and then you will have my thanks for it, as I am always eager to learn the true mechanics of the game. Although I hope any testing evidence to the contrary explains how the total number of candles (in my first test from above) did not stay the same. As I can not see how that can happen if the theory that "a successful temple check produces a candle that has to go somewhere" is the actual mechanic.
	
